# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# .env.example — Environment Variable Reference
#
# WHAT IS THIS FILE?
#   This file lists every environment variable the application needs.
#   It contains EXAMPLE values (not real secrets) so other developers
#   know what to set up without seeing your actual secrets.
#
# HOW TO USE:
#   1. Copy this file:  cp .env.example .env
#   2. Fill in real values in your .env file
#   3. NEVER commit .env to git (it's in .gitignore)
#
# HOW SPRING READS THESE:
#   In application.properties, reference them like:
#     jwt.secret=${JWT_SECRET}
#     jwt.expiration-ms=${JWT_EXPIRATION_MS:86400000}   ← default if not set
#
#   Spring Boot reads environment variables automatically at startup.
#   In IntelliJ: Run Configuration → Environment Variables → add them there.
#   On a server: export JWT_SECRET=... in your shell or Docker environment.
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# The secret key used to sign JWT tokens.
# Must be at least 32 characters for HMAC-SHA256.
# Generate a strong one with: openssl rand -base64 64
JWT_SECRET=replace-this-with-a-real-long-random-secret-at-least-32-chars

# How long a JWT token stays valid (in milliseconds).
# 86400000 = 24 hours
JWT_EXPIRATION_MS=86400000

